statement:
Find a vector of length $1$ that is parallel to the line given by the
equations

\begin{align*}\left\{ \begin{aligned} y-z &= 1 \\ 2x+y+z &= 2 \end{aligned}\right.\end{align*}

sols:
Since a vector on the line has to be on each plane, it has to be a
solution of a linear system. We have the following equations

\begin{align*}\left\{
\begin{aligned}
y-z&=1\\
2x+y+z&=2
\end{aligned}\right.\end{align*}

which is a linear system with 2 equations in 3 unknowns. We can write it
in an augmented matrix as

\begin{align*}\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}
0  &  1  &  -1  &  1\\
2  &  1  &  1  &  2
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

We will swap the first two rows and then row reduce to get

\begin{align*}\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}
1  &  0  &  1  &  1/2\\
0  &  1  &  -1  &  1
\end{array}\right].\end{align*}

We notice there is a free variable and we let \emph{x} = \emph{t}. We
then get

\begin{align*}
z&=\frac{1}{2}-t\\
y&=1+z=\frac{3}{2}-t\end{align*}

Therefore we get that the solution, \textbf{s}, is

\begin{align*}\mathbf{s}=\mathbf{s}_0+t\mathbf{v}=\left[0,\frac{3}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right]+t[1,-1,-1].\end{align*}

The direction part of the line, \textbf{v} is {[}1,-1,-1{]}. However to
make it length 1 we must divide by its magnitude,
$|\mathbf{v}|=\sqrt{3}$ to get,

\begin{align*}\mathbf{\hat{v}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}[1,-1,-1]\end{align*}

just like in
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2011/Question_A16/Solution_1}{solution
1}.
